seless care and toil.
Illness, pain, itching—before the child speaks, the mother already worries;
Coming and going, rising and resting—before the body moves, the heart is already mindful.
Seeing the child laugh or cry, she is moved to sorrow or joy;
Watching its first steps, she is struck with alarm or delight.
She endures hunger to feed her child,
Bears cold to clothe her son.

Longing for the child’s success, her eyes grow weary with waiting;
Yearning for its marriage, her heart finds no rest.

ubtle and serene.
Extracting lead and adding mercury—causing the two eights of yin to dissolve;
Refining bones and forging form—enabling the nine threes of yang to grow.
The source of water, clear or turbid—distinguished at the moment of *Jiji*;
The inner landscape, true or void—recognized in the state of *Zuowang*.

The profound subtleties of the mysterious mechanism are difficult to fully express. Yet the wondrous principles of *Lingbao* can be used to enter sagehood and transcend the mundane.

